t="horizontal" data-via="digitaltrends">Tweet</a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js"></script></div></li></ul></div><div class="text clearfix"><p><a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/tech-trends.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-280457" title="tech-trends" src="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/tech-trends-650x364.jpg" alt="" width="650" height="364" /></a></p><p class="excerpt"><strong>From tablets to motion gaming and Internet streaming boxes for your TV, we round up the hottest holiday tech trends of 2010 and offer our picks for some of the best to buy.</strong></p><p><a title="2010 Holiday Gift Guide " href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/holiday-gift-guide/"><img class="size-full wp-image-281069 alignleft" title="holiday-gift-guide-360-embed" src="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/holiday-gift-guide-360-embed.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="53" /></a>In the toy world, you may remember the year of Cabbage Patch dolls, the year of Furby, and the year of Tickle Me Elmo. In the tech world, it’s more like the year of the netbook, year of the Wii, and year of the Kindle. The items might be glitzier, pricier, and less prone to being relegated to a closet in six weeks, but let’s face it: Grownups want what’s hot just as much as the kids they used to be. And gadgets seem to be it year after year. Looking to tap into the holiday zeitgeist of 2010? Here’s what’s popping up on geek wish lists all over, and some of our favorite items from each category.</p><p><br class="spacer_" /></p><h3>Tablets</h3><p><a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/tablets.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-280456" title="tablets" src="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/tablets-650x365.jpg" alt="" width="650" height="365" /></a>Touch-based computers have kicked around in one form or another for a decade now, but it took Apple’s finesse (and heavy-handed marketing) to convince consumers it was finally time to grope glass. <a title="Apple iPad" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/tablet-reviews/apple-ipad-review/">Apple’s iPad</a> ($499+) sales plowed straight through three million <a title="Apple iPad: Three Million Served" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/gadgets/apple-ipad-three-million-served/">by June</a> of this year and some analysts have even <a title="iPad earns title of fastest selling gadget ever" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/devices/ipad-earns-title-of-fastest-selling-gadget-ever/">declared it</a> the fastest-selling gadget ever. Not surprisingly, imitators have piled on. <a title="Samsung Galaxy Tab Review" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/tablet-reviews/samsung-galaxy-tab-review/">Samsung’s Galaxy Tab</a> (prices vary) may be the best, but we still <a title="Debunking the myth of the iPad slayer" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/gadgets/debunking-the-myth-of-the-ipad-slayer/">wouldn’t recommend</a> one over an iPad unless you’re buying for someone who hisses at the very sight of a fruit logo. If you’re not quite certain you’re ready to buy, keep an eye on <a title="Can Notion Ink’s Adam elevate the tablet to a new generation?" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/gadgets/can-notion-inks-adam-elevate-the-tablet-to-a-new-generation/">Notion Ink’s Adam</a> tablet, which could be leading the entire class to a promising second generation.</p><p><br class="spacer_" /></p><h3>Motion gaming</h3><p><a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/Motion-gaming.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-280453" title="Motion-gaming" src="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/Motion-gaming-650x365.jpg" alt="" width="650" height="365" /></a>Didn’t we already go through this craze in 2006? Well&#8230; yea. But this time Microsoft and Nintendo are leading the charge. Both giants have brought out extensions for their existing consoles that enable the same arm-flailing fun that made the Wii such a hit four years ago. <a title="Microsoft Kinect Review" rel="nofollow" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/game-controller-reviews/microsoft-kinect-review/">Microsoft’s Kinect</a> ($150) is the more innovative, allowing players to ditch controllers all together and merely use the motion of their bodies for control, while<a title="Sony’s PlayStation Move" rel="nofollow" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/hands-on-and-swinging-with-the-playstation-move/"> Sony’s PlayStation Move</a> ($100 for the bundle with one controller) is the more accurate, adding a glowing orb to the top of a Wii-style wand for surgically precise control that will appeal more to hardcore gamers. Kinect looks like the early winner in popularity, but the kiddie-style games out right now might make the Move a better buy for satisfying bloodlust.</p><p><br class="spacer_" /></p><h3>Smartphones</h3><p><a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/smartphones.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-280455" title="smartphones" src="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/smartphones-650x377.jpg" alt="" width="650" height="377" /></a>Phones that do more than just make calls have been gaining steam for years, and this holiday season brings us the best selection yet. While the <a title="Motorola Droid" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/cell-phone-reviews/motorola-droid-review/">Motorola Droid</a> was the only real contender to the<a title="Apple iPhone 3GS 32GB Review" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/cell-phone-reviews/apple-iphone-3gs-32gb-review/"> iPhone 3G S</a> last year, 2010 has brought a slew of heavyweight Android competitors including the <a title="Motorola Droid X Review" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/cell-phone-reviews/motorola-droid-x-review/">Droid X</a> ($200),<a title="HTC EVO 4G Review" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/cell-phone-reviews/htc-evo-4g-review/"> HTC EVO 4G</a> ($200), and <a title="Samsung Captivate Review" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/cell-phone-reviews/samsung-captivate-review/">Samsung Captivate</a> ($200, also known as the Galaxy S). And hey, Apple’s benchmark competitor got even better too, with the<a title="Apple iPhone 4 Review" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/cell-phone-reviews/apple-iphone-4-review/oq=&amp;gs_rfai=&amp;pbx=1&amp;fp=573da4ec7e15bdf2"> iPhone 4</a> ($200+) bringing an insanely high-resolution Retina screen, a 5-megapixel camera that can take the place of a point-and-shoot, and an even faster A4 processor.</p><p><br class="spacer_" /></p><h3>Set-top streamers</h3><p><a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/set-top-streamers.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-280454" title="set-top-streamers" src="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/set-top-streamers-650x339.jpg" alt="" width="650" height="339" /></a>If you haven’t already <a title="Cancel Cable and Save with Free Internet TV" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/home-theater/how-to-cancel-cable-and-get-tv-on-your-pc/">cancelled cable </a>to save money with streaming Internet TV, this is the year to do it. Not surprisingly, Apple and Google lead the charge into the living room; Apple with it’s <a title="Apple TV" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/media-streamer-reviews/apple-tv-review-second-generation/">Apple TV</a> ($99) that now does Netflix streaming, and Google with Google TV, a new platform available on the <a title="Logitech Revue Review" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/media-streamer-reviews/logitech-revue-with-google-tv-review/">Logitech Revue</a> set-top box ($300) and Sony Internet TVs ($600+). If you favor the underdog, <a title="WD Live Plus" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/media-streamer-reviews/western-digital-wd-tv-live-plus-review/">Western Digital WD TV Live Plus </a>($130) plays more file types than the Apple TV while also handling 1080p HD, and D-Link’s Boxee Box ($200) supports just about every format under the sun, 1080p, and has one of the slickest interfaces out there, though it still may have some kinks to work out.</p><p><br class="spacer_" /></p><h3>E-readers</h3><p><a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/ereaders.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-280452" title="ereaders" src="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/ereaders-650x353.jpg" alt="" width="650" height="353" /></a>Why even consider an e-reader with tablets like the iPad around? Display technology, battery life, connectivity, and price. An E-Ink reader is easier on the eyes, can last a month on one charge, the <a title="Barnes &amp; Noble Nook Review" href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/ebook-reader-reviews/barnes-noble-nook-review/">Nook </a>($199) and Kindle ($189) both come with free lifetime 3G access, and both readers have been had prices cut to the bone in order to compete with the likes of the iPad. If you’re on a budget or just a bookworm, they really make more sense. Between the two, we prefer Amazon’s Kindle for its reliability, library, and ease of use.</p> <!-- google_ad_section_end --><div class="contentextra rel"><ul class="related_post"><li> <a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/gadgets/top-holiday-gadgets-2009/" title="2009’s Top Holiday Gadgets"> <img width="163" height="118" src="http://www.digitaltrends.com/wp-content/uploads/cache/2009/10/thumbnail_holiday_gadgets.jpg/163_118_crop_resize.jpg" class="attachment-width=163&amp;height=118&amp;crop=1 wp-post-image" alt="2009’s Top Holiday Gadgets" title="2009’s Top Holiday Gadgets" /> </a> <a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/gadgets/top-holiday-gadgets-2009/" title="2009’s Top Holiday Gadgets">2009’s Top Holiday Gadgets</a></li><li> <a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/buying-guides/the-best-tech-gifts-and-gadgets-for-under-200/" title="The best tech gifts and gadgets for under $200"> <img width="163" height="118" 